ğŸ§  What is an Event?

An **event** is an action that happens in the browser.

ğŸ“Œ Examples:

* User clicks a button
* User types in input
* Page loads
* Form is submitted

JavaScript **listens** to these events and **responds**.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§© Common Types of JavaScript Events

ğŸ–±ï¸ Mouse Events

* `click`
* `dblclick`
* `mouseover`
* `mouseout`
* `mousemove`

---

âŒ¨ï¸ Keyboard Events

* `keydown`
* `keyup`
* `keypress` (deprecated)

---

ğŸ“ Form Events

* `submit`
* `change`
* `focus`
* `blur`
* `input`

---

ğŸŒ Window Events

* `load`
* `resize`
* `scroll`

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš™ï¸ Ways to Handle Events

1ï¸âƒ£ Inline Event Handling âŒ

```html
<button onclick="alert('Clicked')">Click</button>
```

ğŸ“Œ Not recommended

---

2ï¸âƒ£ Event Property âŒ

```js
button.onclick = function () {
  alert("Clicked");
};
```

---

3ï¸âƒ£ addEventListener (Best Practice â­)

```js
button.addEventListener("click", function () {
  alert("Button clicked");
});
```

âœ” Multiple events allowed
âœ” Cleaner code
âœ” Most used in real projects

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  The Event Object

The **event object** contains information about the event.

```js
button.addEventListener("click", function (event) {
  console.log(event);
});
```

Common properties:

* `event.type`
* `event.target`
* `event.preventDefault()`


ğŸš« preventDefault()

Stops default browser behavior.

```js
form.addEventListener("submit", function (e) {
  e.preventDefault();
  console.log("Form submitted");
});
```

ğŸ“Œ Used in:

* Form validation
* SPA navigation

---

ğŸ¯ Event Target

Refers to the element that triggered the event.

```js
event.target.style.backgroundColor = "yellow";
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Event Bubbling (Default Behavior)

Event flows **from child â†’ parent**.

```html
<div id="parent">
  <button id="child">Click</button>
</div>
```

```js
child.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Child clicked");
});

parent.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Parent clicked");
});
```

ğŸ“Œ Output:

```
Child clicked
Parent clicked
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ Event Capturing

Event flows **from parent â†’ child**.

```js
parent.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Parent");
}, true);
```

ğŸ“Œ Third parameter `true` enables capturing

---

âœ‹ stopPropagation()

Stops event bubbling or capturing.

```js
child.addEventListener("click", function (e) {
  e.stopPropagation();
  console.log("Only child");
});
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§© Event Delegation (Very Important â­)

Attach event to parent instead of many children.

```js
list.addEventListener("click", function (e) {
  if (e.target.tagName === "LI") {
    console.log(e.target.textContent);
  }
});
```

ğŸ“Œ Improves performance
ğŸ“Œ Used in dynamic lists (Todo apps)

---

ğŸ§ª Keyboard Event Example

```js
input.addEventListener("keydown", function (e) {
  console.log(e.key);
});
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ“œ Window Events

Page Load

```js
window.addEventListener("load", () => {
  console.log("Page loaded");
});
```

---

Scroll

```js
window.addEventListener("scroll", () => {
  console.log(window.scrollY);
});
```

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âŒ Common Event Mistakes

* Using inline events
* Forgetting `preventDefault`
* Not understanding bubbling
* Attaching too many listeners
* Not removing unused listeners

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ’¡ Best Practices

* Always use `addEventListener`
* Use event delegation
* Keep event handlers small
* Understand bubbling & capturing
* Avoid inline JS

